column130: What evaluation methods that have been published by the author [Metadata: author name] have no evaluation guidelines?

column4:
Based on the provided texts, the majority of the evidence shows that the publications by Davide Arcelli consistently investigate two research objects without associating them with the use of input data. These are:

• First Research Object 2  
• Second Research Object 2

Several sources explicitly state that while a separate contribution (labeled Evidence 2) is described with properties related to input data (with values such as “used: False,” “not available,” or—even conflictingly—in one case “used: True”), neither First Research Object 2 nor Second Research Object 2 is described as using input data [1], [2], [5], [6], [9], [11].

Even where one publication provides additional detail by linking First Research Object 2 with entity names such as “Architecture Design Method,” “Architecture Analysis Method,” “Architecture Description Language,” or “Architectural Aspects” [3], [10], [11], [12], [17], [18], [19], [25], [27], [28], none of these descriptions include any indication of input data being used for the investigation of these objects.

Thus, the coherent final answer is:

The research objects investigated in publications from Davide Arcelli that have not used input data are First Research Object 2 and Second Research Object 2.

column4:
Based solely on the information provided by the various texts, the evaluations of papers on architecture analysis methods include several properties. However, a number of the texts explicitly state that evaluations incorporate a property with a sub‑property construct that bears the name Functional Suitability (see, for example, [2], [15], [18], [19], [24], and [25]). Although other properties—such as Accuracy, Effectiveness, Product Quality, and others—are also mentioned, the frequency and explicit detail found in multiple sources indicate that Functional Suitability is the property that is evaluated most often.

Thus, the final answer is: Functional Suitability.

Based on the provided texts, many of the contributions in Paper Class 2 (i.e. those with a proposal of solution) employ evaluation methods such as “Case Study” and “Technical Experiment.” For example, texts [1] and [2] indicate that a contribution involving a research object related to Architecture Extraction was evaluated using “Case Study,” while texts [8] and [21] also report “Case Study” in papers with a proposal of solution. In contrast, several other texts mention “Technical Experiment” as an explicit evaluation method, but these instances are not linked to a contribution whose evaluated research object is explicitly “Architecture Extraction” (or the equivalent research object) or where the proposal of solution flag is confirmed as True.

Thus, when considering those papers that simultaneously have a proposal of solution (Paper Class 2 with that flag set to True) and investigate the research object Architecture Extraction (or a closely related entity), the only evaluation method explicitly mentioned is “Case Study” ([1], [2], [8], [21]). 

It is important to note, however, that while additional evaluation methods appear in the texts overall, none of them are explicitly connected to papers meeting both criteria as clearly as “Case Study.”

column4:
Based solely on the provided texts, the evaluation method applied most often in 2020 is Technical Experiment. Several sources report its use explicitly in 2020-based papers ([1], [8], [10], [11], [14], [17], [19], [20], [24], [26]). column4:
Between 2019 and 2021, the provided texts only explicitly indicate that research objects evaluated using grounded theory were published in 2019. For instance, one work was evaluated using grounded theory as part of its contribution "Supporting Architectural Decision Making on Data Management in Microservice Architectures" [1], another was evaluated similarly in "Guiding Architectural Decision Making on Service Mesh Based Microservice Architectures" [4], and a study on Stack Overflow ("How Developers Discuss Architecture Smells? An Exploratory Study on Stack Overflow") also applied grounded theory in its evaluation [6]. None of the texts mention any research objects evaluated with grounded theory in 2020 or 2021, nor do they provide any distribution beyond 2019 [2][3][5][7][8].

column130: What is the proportion of the research objects that are used in conjunction with the evaluation method [Content Data: evaluation method name] between [Metadata: year] and [Metadata: year]?

column4:
Based on the provided partial answers, there is agreement that between 2019 and 2021 exactly one research object was evaluated using the Argumentation method. Some sources ([2], [3], and [5]) indicate that the work—whichever its title—was published in 2020 and evaluated with Argumentation. On the other hand, [4] explicitly names a research object published in 2019 undergoing an evaluation by Argumentation and does not mention any additional objects in 2020 or 2021. Despite this slight discrepancy regarding the specific publication year (2019 versus 2020), all sources converge on the point that only one such research object falls into the 2019–2021 period. Therefore, the final distribution is that one research object evaluated with the evaluation method Argumentation was published between 2019 and 2021 [1][2][3][4][5].

column4:
Below is a synthesis of the provided partial answers regarding the distribution of evaluation methods applied in publications that evaluate compatibility between 2017 and 2019:

• In 2017 several publications are reported to have evaluated compatibility. For example, one 2017 publication applied evaluation methods including Argumentation, Technical Experiment, and Motivating Example [1]. Another 2017 work is described as having used Technical Experiment, Questionnaire, and Controlled Experiment [2]. Additional 2017 cases include a publication employing Verification and Technical Experiment [15], one applying Grounded Theory [16], another using Technical Experiment from an Evaluation Method List [17], a study evaluated with Field Experiment [18], and a publication that again adopted Technical Experiment [19].

• In 2019 multiple publications evaluated compatibility using a variety of methods. One publication (focused on “Mitigating the Influence of Embedded Software Development Environments and Toolsets (ESDT) on Software Architecture”) applied Technical Experiment [7]. Another project from 2019 employed Focus Group and Questionnaire [4], while a further publication used Technical Experiment in its evaluation [6]. In addition, a 2019 publication on agile architecting in automotive settings used Interview [8]; another reported using Questionnaire [9] and yet another explicitly applied Technical Experiment [10]. Evaluations in 2019 also include work that used a Case Study methodology [11, 14, 20], one evaluation that employed Motivating Example alongside properties like Functional Suitability and Product Quality [12], and a publication that used Field Experiment [13].

Thus, among publications that evaluate compatibility:
 – In 2017 the evaluation methods include Argumentation, Technical Experiment, Motivating Example, Questionnaire, Controlled Experiment, Verification, Grounded Theory, and Field Experiment [1, 2, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19].
 – In 2019 the methods are distributed as Technical Experiment, Focus Group, Questionnaire, Interview, Case Study, Motivating Example (plus additional properties such as Functional Suitability and Product Quality), and Field Experiment [4, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 20].

There is no explicit evidence in the provided texts about any evaluation methods applied in 2018.

column4:
Based on the provided texts, the following 2019 papers explicitly investigate or are described in terms that indicate an investigation into architectural assumptions:

• [1] “The Safety Analysis Method for Cooperative Driving Systems” explicitly states that it investigates architectural assumptions.  
• [4] “Improving the Consistency and Usefulness of Architecture Descriptions: Guidelines for Architects” contributes a research object labeled “Architectural Assumptions.”  
• [12] “Aspect-Oriented Modeling of Technology Heterogeneity in Microservice Architecture” is explicitly identified as meeting the criteria for investigating architectural topics, including its association with Architecture Design Method.  
• [14] “A Four-Layer Architecture Pattern for Constructing and Managing Digital Twins” is clearly noted to address architectural assumptions.  
• [19] “Component-Based Refinement and Verification of Information-Flow Security Policies for Cyber-Physical Microservice Architectures” is associated with an “Architecture Analysis Method,” which indicates that it investigates issues related to architectural assumptions.

These five works are the papers from 2019 that, according to the provided texts, investigate architectural assumptions.

• In contrast, partial answer [2] reports that “A Platform Architecture for Multi‐Tenant Blockchain‐Based Systems” (published in 2019) meets both conditions, ranking it first (and only) when ordered by descending publication year.

• The remaining partial answers ([3]–[6]) state that the other mentioned papers either use a different evaluation method (for example, Case Study, Interview) or do not include Ingo Weber as an author. In these texts it is concluded that no paper satisfies both criteria.

Thus, while two separate partial answers identify one paper each that meets the conditions—one paper from 2017 [1] and one paper from 2019 [2]—the other texts indicate that no paper satisfies both conditions. In summary, based solely on the provided texts there is a conflict: one source identifies a 2017 paper and another a 2019 paper as fulfilling both criteria, whereas the other texts dispute that any paper meets both criteria.

column4:
Based on the provided texts, two sources explicitly list publications that meet both criteria—being classified as validation research and evaluated using the grounded theory method. According to source [7], “Architectural Technical Debt: A Grounded Theory” (2020) is identified as validation research whose evaluation employs grounded theory. Likewise, source [1] indicates that “On Service-Orientation for Automotive Software” (2017) is also classified as validation research and is evaluated using grounded theory. Consequently, when sorting these publications from newest to oldest, the list is as follows:

1. Architectural Technical Debt: A Grounded Theory (2020) [7]
2. On Service-Orientation for Automotive Software (2017) [1]

It should be noted that several other texts (e.g., [2], [3], [4], [5], [6] and so on) mention publications evaluated with grounded theory or classified as validation research but conclude that no publication meets both criteria. However, the two sources above are the only ones that explicitly report a publication fulfilling both properties.

[1] Source: On Service-Orientation for Automotive Software, 10.1109/ICSA.2017.20
[2] Source: CAPS: Architecture Description of Situational Aware Cyber Physical Systems, 10.1109/ICSA.2017.21
[3] Source: Supporting Architectural Decision Making on Data Management in Microservice Architectures, 10.1007/978-3-030-29983-5_2

[7] Source: Architectural Technical Debt: A Grounded Theory, 10.1007/978-3-030-58923-3_14

column4:
The provided texts offer conflicting accounts. Some sources claim that one paper investigating Architecture Evolution appears in a given year, while others indicate that the only such paper was published in a different year. For example, one group of texts indicates that the only paper related to Architecture Evolution was published in 2019, leaving both 2020 and 2021 with 0 papers [1, 4]. In contrast, another set of texts claims that a paper was published in 2021 investigating Architecture Evolution – for instance, “Continuous API Evolution in Heterogenous Enterprise Software Systems” and “Enabling Consistency between Software Artefacts for Software Adaption and Evolution” are both cited with publication dates in 2021 [2, 3, 8]. Meanwhile, yet another group points to one paper in 2020 (e.g., “Architectural Concerns for Digital Twin of the Organization,” “Incremental Calibration of Architectural Performance Models with Parametric Dependencies,” and “Butterfly Space: An Architectural Approach for Investigating Performance Issues”) with no corresponding paper in 2021 [5, 6, 9]. Finally, one source mentions a 2021 paper (“Architectural Decay as Predictor of Issue- and Change-Proneness”) though without explicit association to Architecture Evolution [7].

Thus, depending on which textual account is followed the number of papers investigating Architecture Evolution would be:
• According to sources [1] and [4]: 2020 – 0 papers; 2021 – 0 papers.
• According to sources [5], [6], and [9]: 2020 – 1 paper; 2021 – 0 papers.
• According to sources [2], [3], and [8]: 2020 – 0 papers; 2021 – 1 paper.
• Source [7] adds an additional claim for 2021 with 1 paper, though without clarifying its investigation of Architecture Evolution.

Because the provided texts do not consistently agree on which papers actually investigate Architecture Evolution in 2020 versus 2021, there is no single definitive answer. One must note these discrepancies when considering the final counts.

[2] Source: Continuous API Evolution in Heterogenous Enterprise Software Systems, 10.1109/ICSA51549.2021.00014
[3] Source: Enabling Consistency between Software Artefacts for Software Adaption and Evolution, 10.1109/ICSA51549.2021.00009
[4] Source: An Empirical Study of Architectural Decay in Open-Source Software, 10.1109/ICSA.2018.00027
[5] Source: Architectural Concerns for Digital Twin of the Organization, 10.1007/978-3-030-58923-3_18
[6] Source: Incremental Calibration of Architectural Performance Models with Parametric Dependencies, 10.1109/ICSA47634.2020.00011
[7] Source: Architectural Decay as Predictor of Issue- and Change-Proneness, 10.1109/ICSA51549.2021.00017
[8] Source: Exploring Web Search Engines to Find Architectural Knowledge, 10.1109/ICSA51549.2021.00023
[9] Source: Butterfly Space: An Architectural Approach for Investigating Performance Issues, 10.1109/ICSA47634.2020.00027

column130: Which papers that have been published in the year [Metadata: year] investigate the research object with the name [Content Data: research object name] and have not used input data in their work?

column4:
Below is a synthesis of the explicit evidence from the provided texts. Several works are described as investigating architecture decision making and, according to multiple sources, have their Evidence 2 contribution use input data that is not available (i.e. “available” is explicitly set to False) and were published in 2018. For example:

• The paper titled "Architectural Design Decisions for Systems Supporting Model-Based Analysis of Runtime Events: A Qualitative Multi-method Study" is explicitly associated with architecture decision making and is reported to have its input data not available [1].

• "Understanding Architecture Decisions in Context" investigates architecture decision making and includes explicit statements that its Evidence 2 contribution uses input data that is not available [2].

• "Empirical Insights into the Evolving Role of Architects in Decision-Making in an Agile Context" is also described as investigating architecture decision making, was published in 2018, and includes explicit evidence that its input data is not available [9].

• Similarly, "Abstraction Layered Architecture: Writing Maintainable Embedded Code" and "Two Architectural Threat Analysis Techniques Compared" are presented as papers concerned with architectural (and by extension, architectural decision making) topics and are noted—through their Evidence 2 attributes—to have input data that is not available in 2018 [16] [17].

It should be noted that while some papers (and in some cases even within the same paper) are reported with conflicting remarks on input data availability, the synthesis above focuses on those instances where explicit statements indicate that input data is not available. Thus, based on the provided texts, the papers that investigate architecture decision making and have their input data marked as not available in 2018 include:

 – "Architectural Design Decisions for Systems Supporting Model-Based Analysis of Runtime Events: A Qualitative Multi-method Study" [1]  
 – "Understanding Architecture Decisions in Context" [2]  
 – "Empirical Insights into the Evolving Role of Architects in Decision-Making in an Agile Context" [9]  
 – "Abstraction Layered Architecture: Writing Maintainable Embedded Code" [16]  
 – "Two Architectural Threat Analysis Techniques Compared" [17]

These are the works that explicitly meet both criteria according to the provided evidence.

[17] Source: Two Architectural Threat Analysis Techniques Compared, 10.1007/978-3-030-00761-4_23

column4:
Based on the provided texts, two papers are identified that meet all three criteria—that they use the Focus Group evaluation method, were published in 2017, and did not use input data:

• According to [4], the paper "On Cognitive Biases in Architecture Decision Making" is associated with a Focus Group evaluation and was published in 2017. Although some descriptions mention input data, explicit details indicate that the input data was not actually used.

• As noted in [7], "Architectural Assumptions and Their Management in Industry – An Exploratory Study" was published in 2017 and evaluated with the Focus Group method. Despite one description suggesting that input data might be utilized, other passages confirm that input data was not available (i.e., not used).

Thus, the papers "On Cognitive Biases in Architecture Decision Making" [4] and "Architectural Assumptions and Their Management in Industry – An Exploratory Study" [7] are the ones with the Focus Group method published in 2017 that did not use input data.

column130: How are the papers that investigate the research object with the name [Content Data: research object name] distributed between the publication year [year 1] and [year 2]?

column4:
The available texts present two conflicting accounts of the distribution between 2018 and 2020. Some sources consistently report that one paper investigating the object architecture description was published in 2018 with no corresponding publications in 2019 or 2020 ([1], [2], [3], [5], [6], [7], [10], [17], [18], [20], [21], [22], [24]). In contrast, a different set of sources indicates that the only paper on this topic was published in 2020—with no such paper detected for 2018 (or 2019) ([4], [8], [9], [11], [12], [13], [14], [15], [16], [19], [23], [25], [26], [27], [28], [29], [30]). 

Thus, based solely on the provided texts, the investigation of the object architecture description appears to be represented by a single paper in one of the two distinct years—either 2018 or 2020—while no papers from 2019 are mentioned. The final answer therefore depends on which set of texts is given precedence, but the overall picture is that only one paper is identified in the timeframe, with the year of publication being either 2018 or 2020 according to the respective sources.
